Let's define a function for plotting a heatmap with more descriptive names.

labelled_heatmap <- function(data, meta) {
    corrs <- cor(data)
    display.names <- paste(meta$Host_Plant, meta$Tissue, meta$Host.Plant.use, 
        sep = ".")
    names(display.names) <- meta$Customer_ID
    colnames(corrs) <- display.names[colnames(corrs)]
    rownames(corrs) <- colnames(corrs)
    pheatmap(corrs, cex = 0.8)
}

… and some functions for normalization and pre-processing of counts.

normalize.voom <- function(counts) {
    require(limma)
    return(voom(counts)$E)
}

cpm.tmm <- function(counts, groups = NA) {
    require(edgeR)
    if (is.na(groups)) {
        d <- DGEList(counts = counts)
    } else {
        d <- DGEList(counts = counts, group = groups)
    }
    d <- calcNormFactors(d, method = "TMM")
    return(cpm(d, normalized.lib.sizes = TRUE))
}

Try differential expression analysis in DESeq2. We start by just looking at core vs extended within the gut samples. 

# DESeq2
subset <- meta[which(meta$Tissue == "Gut"), "Customer_ID"]
columns <- intersect(subset, colnames(counts))
meta.gut <- meta[which(meta$Tissue == "Gut"), ]

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = counts[, columns], colData = meta.gut[, 
    c("Customer_ID", "Host.Plant.use", "Phylogeny_group", "Host_Plant")], design = ~Host.Plant.use)

Differential expression analysis using all samples, with tissue as a factor.

columns <- intersect(meta$Customer_ID, colnames(counts))
counts_ <- counts[, columns]

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = counts_, colData = meta[, c("Customer_ID", 
    "Host.Plant.use", "Phylogeny_group", "Host_Plant", "Tissue", "Family")], 
    design = ~Tissue + Family + Host.Plant.use)

## Usage note: the following factors have 3 or more levels:
## 
## Tissue
## 
## For DESeq2 versions < 1.3, if you plan on extracting results for
## these factors, we recommend using betaPrior=FALSE as an argument
## when calling DESeq().
## As currently implemented in version 1.2, the log2 fold changes can
## vary if the base level is changed, when extracting results for a

Plot some examples of genes with low p values. These are differentially expressed in core vs extended overall, that is, considering all tissues.

library(lattice)

for (gene in head(rownames(sig.o))) {
    expr <- t(counts_[gene, ]/colSums(counts_))
    temp <- data.frame(expr = expr, tissue = meta$Tissue, core_vs_ext = meta$Host.Plant.use)
    print(bwplot(expr ~ core_vs_ext | tissue, data = temp, main = gene))
}
